  "chunk_index": 23,
  "summary": "At the Chateau de Vronk, David Hunter promises Rosaline that they will move to the south of France or America once their current situation is resolved. To manage her anxiety, he encourages her to take bromide tranquilizers prescribed by Dr. Klopp. Despite the looming interrogation, David feels no regret regarding his risky lifestyle and whispers to Rosaline that he did not kill the deceased man.\n\nAn inquest is held at the grain market, presided over by Coroner Mr. Peppermarsh and Constable Spence. Attendees include the Kloes family, Mrs. Marchmont, Lynn, and Major Porter. Dr. Leonine Clode testifies that the deceased, identified as Inoak Jadon from Cape Town, was found face down with a head injury caused by fire tongs. The forensic officer notes the attack was brutal, involving five to six blows to the base of the skull, some of which were delivered post-mortem. The victim was approximately forty-five years old and in good health.\n\nBeatrice Lippincott testifies that Jadon arrived on Friday but failed to provide a ration book. She also recounts a conversation she overheard, which she reported to Rolly Claude. Guy Soames questions whether Jadon explicitly identified himself as Robert Underdahl, to which Beatrice replies he did not. Rolly Claude testifies that he met the deceased at 8:55 PM and that Jadon claimed he could not be proven wrong without his cooperation, laughing about Robert André being alive.\n\nDavid Hunter is called to testify. He denies Beatrice's version of events, claiming Jadon only asked for financial assistance and never mentioned Robert André being alive. David attributes Beatrice's testimony to the errors of an eavesdropper. He denies visiting the deceased on Tuesday and asserts that his sister has become a target for parasites since inheriting her late husband's money.",
